<section xml:id="factoring-special-products" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"> 

  <title>   Factoring Special Products  </title> 

  <introduction> <alert> Objective:  Identify and factor special products including a difference of squares, perfect squares, and sum and difference of cubes. </alert> </introduction> 

   <p> 
When factoring there are a few special products that, if we can recognize them, can help us factor polynomials. The first is one we have seen before. When multiplying special products we found that a sum and a difference could multiply to a difference of squares. Here we will use this special product to help us factor.
   </p>

   <p>
     <me> \textbf{ Difference of Squares: } \mathbf{ a^2 - b^2 = (a + b)(a - b)}</me>
   </p>

   <p>
If we are subtracting two perfect squares then it will always factor to the sum and
difference of the square roots.
   </p>

  <example>
    <md> 
      <mrow> x^2 - 16 \amp \quad  \text{ Subtracting two perfect squares, the square roots are $x$ and $4$     }   </mrow> 
      <mrow> (x + 4)(x - 4) \amp\quad  \text{  Our Solution   }  </mrow> 
    </md>
  </example> 

  <example>
    <md> 
      <mrow> 9a^2 - 25b^2 \amp \quad  \text{ Subtracting two perfect squares, the square roots are $3a$ and $5b$     }   </mrow> 
      <mrow> (3a + 5b)(3a - 5b) \amp\quad  \text{  Our Solution   }  </mrow> 
    </md>
  </example> 

  <p>
    It is important to note, that a sum of squares will never factor. It is always prime. This can be seen if we try to use the ac method to factor <m>x^2 + 36</m>.
  </p>

  <example>
    <md> 
      <mrow> x^2 +36 \amp \quad  \text{  No $bx$ term, we use $0x$.    }   </mrow> 
      <mrow> x^2 + 0x + 36 \amp\quad  \text{  Multiply to $36$, add to $0$   }  </mrow> 
      <mrow> 1\times 36,\ 2\times 18,\ 3\times 12,\ 4\times 9,\ 6\times 6 \amp\quad  \text{  No combinations that multiply to $36$ add to $0$   }  </mrow> 
      <mrow> \text{ Prime, cannot factor } \amp\quad  \text{  Our Solution   }  </mrow> 
    </md>
  </example> 

  <p>
    It turns out that a sum of squares is always prime.
  </p>

   <p>
     <me> \textbf{ Sum of Squares: } \mathbf{ a^2 + b^2 = } \textbf{ Prime}</me>
   </p>

   <p>
     A great example where we see a sum of squares comes from factoring a difference
of <m>4</m>th powers. Because the square root of a fourth power is a square <m>(\sqrt{a^4} = a^2)</m>, we can factor a difference of fourth powers just like we factor a difference of squares, to a sum and difference of the square roots. This will give us two factors, one which will be a prime sum of squares, and a second which will be a difference of squares which we can factor again. This is shown in the following examples.
   </p>

  <example>
    <md> 
      <mrow> a^4-b^4 \amp \quad  \text{ Difference of squares with roots $a^2$ and $b^2$     }   </mrow> 
      <mrow> (a^2 + b^2)(a^2 - b^2) \amp\quad  \text{ The first factor is prime, the second is a difference of squares!    }  </mrow> 
      <mrow>(a^2+b^2)(a+b)(a-b)  \amp\quad  \text{  Our Solution   }  </mrow> 
    </md>
  </example> 

  <example>
    <md> 
      <mrow> x^4-16 \amp \quad  \text{  Difference of squares with roots $x^2$ and  } 4   </mrow> 
      <mrow>  (x^2+4)(x^2-4) \amp\quad  \text{  The first factor is prime, the second is a difference of squares!   }  </mrow> 
      <mrow> (x^2+4)(x+2)(x-2) \amp\quad  \text{  Our Solution   }  </mrow> 
    </md>
  </example> 

  <p>
Another factoring shortcut is the perfect square. We had a shortcut for multi- plying a perfect square which can be reversed to help us factor a perfect square.
  </p>

  <p>
    <me> \textbf{ Perfect Squares: } \mathbf{ a^2 +2ab + b^2 = (a+b)^2} </me>
  </p>

  <p>
    A perfect square can be difficult to recognize at first glance, but if we use the ac method and get two of the same numbers we know we have a perfect square. Then we can just factor using the square roots of the first and last terms and the sign from the middle. This is shown in the following examples.
  </p>

    <example>
    <md> 
      <mrow> x^2-6x+9 \amp \quad  \text{   Multiply to $9$, add to  } -6    </mrow> 
      <mrow>  \amp\quad  \text{  The numbers are $- 3$ and $- 3$, the same! Perfect square   }  </mrow> 
      <mrow>(x - 3)^2  \amp\quad  \text{   Use square roots from first and last terms and sign from the middle  }  </mrow> 
    </md>
  </example> 

  <example>
    <md> 
      <mrow> 4x^2 + 20xy + 25y^2 \amp \quad  \text{ Multiply to $100$, add to $20$  }   </mrow> 
      <mrow>  \amp\quad  \text{  The numbers are $10$ and $10$, the same! Perfect square   }  </mrow> 
      <mrow>(2x + 5y)^2  \amp\quad  \text{   Use square roots from first and last terms and sign from the middle  }  </mrow> 
    </md>
  </example> 

    <p> <alert> World View Note:</alert> The first known record of work with polynomials comes from the Chinese around <m>200</m> BC. Problems would be written as “three sheafs of a good crop, two sheafs of a mediocre crop, and one sheaf of a bad crop sold for <m>29</m> dou. This would be the polynomial (trinomial) <m>3x + 2y + z = 29</m>. </p> 

    <p>
      Another factoring shortcut has cubes. With cubes we can either do a sum or a difference of cubes. Both sum and difference of cubes have very similar factoring formulas
      <me> \textbf{ Sum of Cubes: } \mathbf{ a^3 +b^3 =(a+b)(a^2 -ab+b^2)}</me>
      <me> \textbf{ Difference of Cubes: } \mathbf{ a^3 -b^3 =(a-b)(a^2 +ab+b^2)}</me>
      Comparing the formulas you may notice that the only difference is the signs in between the terms. One way to keep these two formulas straight is to think of SOAP. S stands for Same sign as the problem. If we have a sum of cubes, we add first, a difference of cubes we subtract first. O stands for Opposite sign. If we have a sum, then subtraction is the second sign, a difference would have addition for the second sign. Finally, AP stands for Always Positive. Both formulas end with addition. The following examples show factoring with cubes.
    </p>

  <example>
    <md> 
      <mrow> m^3 - 27 \amp \quad  \text{   We have cube roots $m$ and  } 3   </mrow> 
      <mrow> (m \quad 3)(m^2 \quad 3m\quad  9)  \amp\quad  \text{ Use formula, use SOAP to fill in signs    }  </mrow> 
      <mrow> (m - 3)(m^2 + 3m + 9) \amp\quad  \text{  Our Solution   }  </mrow> 
    </md>
  </example> 

  <example>
    <md> 
      <mrow> 125p^3 + 8r^3 \amp \quad  \text{  We have cube roots $5p$ and  } 2r   </mrow> 
      <mrow> (5p\quad 2r)(25p^2\quad 10r\quad 4r^2) \amp\quad  \text{ Use formula, use SOAP to fill in signs    }  </mrow> 
      <mrow>  (5p+ 2r)(25p^2-10r+4r^2) \ \amp\quad  \text{  Our Solution   }  </mrow> 
    </md>
  </example> 

  <p>
The previous example illustrates an important point. When we fill in the trino- mial’s first and last terms we square the cube roots <m>5p</m> and <m>2r</m>. Often students forget to square the number in addition to the variable. Notice that when done correctly, both get cubed.
  </p>
  
  <p>
Often after factoring a sum or difference of cubes, students want to factor the second factor, the trinomial further. As a general rule, this factor will always be prime (unless there is a GCF which should have been factored out before using cubes rule).
  </p>

  <p>
The following table sumarizes all of the shortcuts that we can use to factor special products.
  </p>

  <p> <me> \textbf{Factoring Special Products} </me>
    <md> 
      <mrow> \text{ Difference of Squares } \amp \quad   a^2-b^2=(a+b)(a-b)  </mrow> 
      <mrow>\text{ Sum of Squares } \amp\quad a^2+b^2=\text{ Prime }  </mrow> 
      <mrow> \text{ Perfect Square } \amp\quad  a^2 +2ab+b^2 =(a+b)^2  </mrow> 
      <mrow> \text{ Sum of Cubes } \amp\quad   a^3 +b^3 =(a+b)(a^2 -ab+b^2) </mrow> 
      <mrow> \text{ Difference of Cubes }\amp\quad  a^3-b^3=(a-b)(a^2+ab+b^2)  </mrow> 
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    As always, when factoring special products it is important to check for a GCF first. Only after checking for a GCF should we be using the special products. This is shown in the following examples.
  </p>

  <example>
    <md> 
      <mrow> 72x^2-2 \amp \quad  \text{  GCF is  } 2    </mrow> 
      <mrow>  2(36x^2 - 1) \amp\quad  \text{   Difference of Squares, square roots are $6x$ and  } 1  </mrow> 
      <mrow>  2(6x + 1)(6x - 1) \amp\quad  \text{  Our Solution   }  </mrow> 
    </md>
  </example> 

  <example>
    <md> 
      <mrow>  48x^2y - 24xy + 3y \amp \quad  \text{ GCF is  } 3y   </mrow> 
      <mrow>  3y(16x^2 - 8x + 1) \amp\quad  \text{ Multiply to $16$ add to  } 8  </mrow> 
      <mrow>  \amp\quad  \text{  The numbers are $4$ and $4$, the same! Perfect Square   }  </mrow> 
      <mrow>3y(4x - 1)^2  \amp\quad  \text{  Our Solution   }  </mrow> 
    </md>
  </example> 

    <example>
    <md> 
      <mrow> 128a^4b^2 + 54a b^5 \amp \quad  \text{ GCF is  } 2a b^2   </mrow> 
      <mrow> 2ab^2(64a^3 + 27b^3) \amp\quad  \text{ Sum of cubes! Cube roots are $4a$ and  } 3b  </mrow> 
      <mrow> 2ab^2(4a + 3b)(16a^2 - 12a b + 9b^2) \amp\quad  \text{  Our Solution   }  </mrow> 
    </md>
  </example> 

